The screen shows a web browser displaying a p5.js Web Editor, likely within an instructional coding context related to DAM Museum's artists/timelines. The visible portion of the code editor contains JavaScript, and appears to be setting up a grid-based pattern. The visual output is a canvas filled with a dense arrangement of light gray squares, many containing smaller white squares within them. The UI indicates the file name is `p5.js` and the tab title includes "DAM Museum".

```javascript
// p5.js Web Editor
// https://editor.p5js.org/

function setup() {
  createCanvas(600, 400);
  noLoop(); // Only draw once
}

function draw() {
  background(240);
  let gridSize = 50;

  for (let x = 0; x < width; x += gridSize) {
    for (let y = 0; y < height; y += gridSize) {
      rect(x, y, gridSize, gridSize);

      // Add a smaller square inside some of the larger squares
      if (random(1) > 0.75) {
        fill(255); // White color for the inner square
        rect(x + gridSize/4, y + gridSize/4, gridSize/2, gridSize/2);
        noFill(); // Reset fill for the next square
      } else {
          noFill();
      }

    }
  }
}
```

The right side of the screen displays information about Vera Molnar and her work, "Computer drawing with plotter on Benson paper," from 1976. A text description accompanies the image of the artwork, along with copyright information.

